What is <code>is</code>? <p><code>is</code> is a TypeScript library used for type checking and validation. It provides a simple way to check the type of a value, making it useful for ensuring data integrity and preventing errors in your applications.</p> How do I install <code>is</code>? <p>To install <code>is</code>, run the following command in your terminal:</p> <pre><code>npm install is
</code></pre> <p>or if you're using Yarn:</p> <pre><code>yarn add is
</code></pre> What are the basic usage and examples of <code>is</code>? <p><code>is</code> provides a simple API for type checking. Here are some examples:</p> <pre><code>import is from 'is';

console.log(is.string('🦄')); //=&gt; true
console.log(is.number(42)); //=&gt; true
console.log(is.boolean(true)); //=&gt; true
console.log(is.array([1, 2, 3])); //=&gt; true
console.log(is.object({})); //=&gt; true
</code></pre> <p>You can also use it to check for more specific types:</p> <pre><code>import is from 'is';

console.log(is.email('user@example.com')); //=&gt; true
console.log(is.url('https://example.com')); //=&gt; true
</code></pre> How do I configure <code>is</code>? <p>By default, <code>is</code> works out of the box without requiring any configuration. However, if you need to extend or customize its behavior, you can create a custom instance:</p> <pre><code>import { createIs } from 'is';

const customIs = createIs({
  // your custom configuration
});
</code></pre> <p>Refer to the README for more information on custom configuration options.</p> What if I'm getting a false positive or false negative with <code>is</code>? <p>If you're getting incorrect results, make sure you're using the correct method for the type you're checking. For example, <code>is.string()</code> will return <code>false</code> for numbers or booleans, even if they could be represented as strings.</p> <p>If you're still having issues, check the TypeScript definitions or source code for more insight into how <code>is</code> works.</p> Can I contribute to <code>is</code>? <p>Yes! Contributions are welcome. Before submitting a pull request, please ensure your changes are tested and follow the existing coding style.</p> <p>To get started:</p> <ol> <li>Fork the repository</li> <li>Run <code>npm install</code> or <code>yarn install</code></li> <li>Make your changes</li> <li>Run <code>npm test</code> or <code>yarn test</code> to ensure tests pass</li> </ol> How do I report a bug or request a feature? <p>To report a bug or request a feature, please open an issue on the <code>is</code> repository.</p> <p>When reporting a bug, provide:</p> <ul> <li>A clear description of the issue</li> <li>A code example that reproduces the issue</li> <li>The expected behavior</li> </ul> <p>When requesting a feature, provide:</p> <ul> <li>A clear description of the feature</li> <li>A use case that motivates the feature</li> </ul> Is <code>is</code> compatible with my existing TypeScript version? <p><code>is</code> is written in TypeScript and tested against the latest versions. However, it should be compatible with TypeScript 4.x and later.</p> <p>If you're experiencing issues with compatibility, please open an issue with details about your setup.</p> Can I use <code>is</code> in a browser environment? <p>Yes, <code>is</code> can be used in a browser environment. However, you may need to use a bundler like Webpack or Rollup to include it in your project.</p> <p>Make sure to check the README for more information on browser support.</p> How do I use <code>is</code> with other libraries or frameworks? <p><code>is</code> is designed to be a standalone library, but it can be used with other libraries and frameworks.</p> <p>For example, you can use it with React or Angular to validate props or form inputs:</p> <pre><code>import React from 'react';
import is from 'is';

const MyComponent = ({ name }) =&gt; {
  if (!is.string(name)) {
    throw new Error('Name must be a string');
  }
  // ...
};
</code></pre> <p>Refer to the documentation for your specific library or framework for more information on integration.</p> What is the license for <code>is</code>? <p><code>is</code> is released under the MIT License.</p> Where can I find more information about <code>is</code>? <p>For more information about <code>is</code>, including documentation, examples, and source code, visit the official repository.</p> <p>Generated by DocWalk</p> <p>Unlock Full Documentation</p> <p>This is a preview. Run DocWalk on your own repo for complete API reference across all 7 modules, deeper AI analysis, and more.</p>
